1. Introduction {#sec1}
===============

Adult T-cell leukemia--lymphoma (ATL) is a kind of peripheral T-cell lymphoma caused by human T-cell lymphotropic virus type 1 (HTLV-1) [@bib1]. It is classified into four categories (acute, lymphoma, chronic, and smoldering types) depending on clinical features [@bib2]. ATL is often resistant to chemotherapies, thus resulting in poor prognosis [@bib3]. In this review, we will discuss the recent advances in understanding the pathogenesis of ATL, as well as the novel therapeutic strategies that are being developed to improve the outcomes for patients with this aggressive disease. We will focus on the molecular mechanisms underlying ATL development and progression, including the role of HTLV-1 in immune evasion and the dysregulation of key signaling pathways. Additionally, we will examine the potential of targeted therapies, immune checkpoint inhibitors, and chimeric antigen receptor (CAR) T-cell therapies in the treatment of ATL. Finally, we will highlight the challenges and opportunities in the field, and propose future directions for research aimed at improving the prognosis of ATL patients.

