1. Introduction {#sec1-molecules-21-00781}
===============

Primary liver cancer is a common malignant tumor, and about 260,000 people die from liver cancer all over the world every year. The prognosis of liver cancer is generally poor, with a 5-year survival rate of less than 10% for patients diagnosed with advanced-stage disease. Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) accounts for approximately 80–90% of primary liver cancers, while cholangiocarcinoma (CCA) and other rare liver cancers constitute the remaining portion. HCC is often associated with chronic liver diseases, such as hepatitis B virus (HBV) infection, hepatitis C virus (HCV) infection, and cirrhosis.

