Introduction {#sec1}
============

There have been a number of structural studies on the influenza A virus (e.g. [@bib8; @bib23; @bib59]), which is surrounded by a pleomorphic lipid bilayer envelope that imposes challenges for high-resolution structural characterization. These have provided important details about the morphology of the virions and the distribution of their surface glycoproteins, but structural studies that include detailed analysis of the lipids are lacking. Lipids are integral components of viral membranes, playing crucial roles in viral entry, fusion, stability, and immune evasion. Despite their importance, the lipid composition and organization of viral envelopes have been largely overlooked in structural investigations. This is due, in part, to the inherent difficulties in preserving lipids during sample preparation for cryo-electron microscopy (cryo-EM) and X-ray crystallography, the two most common structural biology techniques.

